<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width="95%"><TR><td bgcolor="#F7F7F7"><TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="100%"><TR bgcolor="#9FA6C4"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#000000" FACE="Verdana">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#E8EAF0"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Nostaw</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Hey does any one out there know how to tailor anythig besides the commonly known thing (patchwork, studded, and reinforced) im getting really sick of wasteing money on patterns trying to figure out what else can be made through this skill. Any help that can be given is greatly apreciated. please post replys here or e-mail me at virtadpt@hotmail.com<BR>                  Thanks</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#D9DCE8"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Turlo</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">You can also make backpacks and quivers.  I haven't played too much with these yet.  From what I understand, you need a high quality bear pelt and the pattern.  Backpacks are supposed to be 10-slot.<P>------------------<BR>Turlo Lomon,<BR>Heir to Lomon Manor</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#E8EAF0"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Clawblade</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">yup, backpacks should be your next step, you can find the patterns at most places that sell a large sewing kit, quivers come after backpacks</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#D9DCE8"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Saladdin</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">I'm playing a level 5 Dwarf Paladin and I'm having problems with tailoring. I out 5 points training into tailoring, bought a small sewing kit, a pattern, a scroll with how to sew, and killed a wolf for his pelt. I put everything together and presto: lost the hat pattern and the pelt. I later tried combining rat fur, Deathfist scalps etc.. in the hope of obtaining some kind of patchwork that everyone seems to have, with the same result. My tailoring skill doesn't go up either.<P>Am I doing the right thing ? What should I be combining at this stage in the sewing kit ? Am I supposed to have a patchwork pattern ?<P>Thanks for any help regarding this.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#E8EAF0"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Shon</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">All armor uses the same patterns.  To make patchwork armor you must put the following into your kit:<P>A pattern <BR>A RUINED pelt <P>That is it.  Please note that the type of pelt will determine the size you get (small from wolf, medium from cats, large from bears).  Only RUINED pelts will work for patchwork; skins, medium or high quality pelts are not used for patchwork.  At a skill of 5 you will probably fail.  I currently have a skill of 26 and still fail 20% of the time.  If you fail, everything in the kit is destroyed and you have to get new components to try again.<P>Good luck</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#D9DCE8"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Saladdin</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Thanks.<P>One more: is it worth spending training points on this or should I just continue ruining patterns and skins until the skill goes up ?</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#E8EAF0"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Ralas</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">I personally spent 20 points on tailoring with my human paladin before I even tried it. I was personally making money selling small pw armor to npc's as I could only kill wolves (small) and it is on the race war server hehe.  Also, i think i was getting around 50% chance of making it.. which I still earned money and was leveling up the skill.<BR>I recommend just going to the kit lady and buying tons of patterns at a time. That way you will make less trips through zones.<P>-Ralas of Bertoxxulous</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#D9DCE8"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Daktor</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">also with tayloring armor it is very important to put the "how to sew <whichever> sizes" parchment in your main inventory.  This GREATLY improves your chances to create the armor pieces you are attempting to create.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#E8EAF0"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Mike G.</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">If you can get spider (not spiderling) silk, put two silks in a sewing kit and combine.If you are sucessful, you will get a silk swatch. This should suffice to raise your skill to the point where you will have a reasonable shot at making patchwork. After patchwork becomes trivial, then use your silk swatches to make raw silk armor. Raw silk is in demand by casters and should sell for 1pp per ac or so. </FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#D9DCE8"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Eric Plante</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">There is no proofs that putting the 'How to Sew' scroll or the tailoring book in your main invetory improve your chance to make an item.<P>I once tried it with blacksmithing, I wasn't succeeding more with the book than without, same with fletching book and bower book. I never tried with tailoring book but tailoring seems easier to succeed at than other trade skills(and cheaper too if you only buy the patterns and find the pelts yourself). </FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#E8EAF0"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Eric Plante</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">There is no proofs that putting the 'How to Sew' scroll or the tailoring book in your main invetory improve your chance to make an item.<P>I once tried it with blacksmithing, I wasn't succeeding more with the book than without, same with fletching book and bower book. I never tried with tailoring book but tailoring seems easier to succeed at than other trade skills(and cheaper too if you only buy the patterns and find the pelts yourself). </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE></td></tr></table> 
